{"key":"post-17187466","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>17187466</id>\n<content>I think emphasis on 'nutes' in mushroom growing is misguided.&amp;nbsp; After all, straw has almost no nutes in the traditional sense, yet the biggest mushrooms I've ever grown were on straw.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Adding vermiculite to any bulk substrate will make it perform better.&amp;nbsp; Coir works well when applied as a casing layer or when spawned by grains as a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; When it's used as a casing layer, a good argument could be made that it's simply a top layer of bulk substrate, but whatever it is, it works pretty well.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Mold spores have a hard time germinating on coir for reasons still unknown, but that contaminant resistance makes it a great beginner substrate.&amp;nbsp; Of course, if your spawn is contaminated you're still screwed, with or without coir.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>17187003</prev>\n<first>17184345</first>\n<last>17187466</last>\n<when>1352437186</when>\n<utime>11/09/12 06:59 AM</utime>\n</post>"}